The optical properties of the dots can be tuned, based on their size and composition. As the particle size decreases, the energy difference between energy bands is increased. Smaller particles emit shorter wave lengths (UV region), while larger particles emit longer wavelengths of the infrared region. This phenomenon is called “quantum confinement” and particles smaller than the “Bohr exciton radius” exhibit this property. The Bohr radius determines the type of confinement; e.g., weak confinement is measured for particles with the size of 3–10nm, whereas a strong confinement is for radius less than 3nm. Quantum confinement is the spatial confinement of electron–hole pairs in one or more dimensions within a material. Quantum wells, quantum wire, and QDs exhibit 1D, 2D and 3D confinements, respectively. The confinement of QDs can be analyzed based on the optical data obtained from following techniques;

                        •

Optical absorption: bandgap is probed here. As the nanocrystal size decreases, there is a systemic shift of bandgap edge toward shorter wavelength or blue shifted;


                        •

Raman vibration spectroscopy: it probes vibrational modes of material using laser. Broadening and shrinking of Raman peak shift toward the laser line is observed when nanocrystals becomes more confined;


                        •

Photoluminescence (PL) spectroscopy: It is used for probing the quantum yield (QY).

In atoms, the attractive forces are exerted by the nuclei, whereas in QDs, it is the background charges. As the atoms are brought together in a bulk material, the energy states are nearly continuous bands of states. Reduction in particle size results in the confinement of normally delocalized energy states from the continuous state. Electron–hole pairs become spatially confined when particle size reduction approaches the de Broglie wavelength of electrons in the conduction band. QD bandgaps are tunable by their size and therefore amenable for engineering of their optical and electrical properties. The semiconductors can be of following types;

                        •

Pure or intrinsic semiconductors: the bandgap is very small in these materials with equal numbers of conduction electrons and holes. The electrical conductivity of pure substances increases with increasing temperature;


                        •

Impure or extrinsic semiconductors: impurities or doping agents are added intentionally in small quantities. For example, pentavalent doping agents (As, Sb, P) and trivalent doping agents (Ga, In, P, B).

QDs are an alternative to the traditional organic fluorophore and their advantages are as follows:

                           •

High PL: each nanocrystal emits many more photons and the QY is approximately 20 times brighter;


                           •

High photobleaching threshold: 100–1000 times more than the fluorophores;


                           •

Longer photostability: enabling acquisition of image over long period of time;


                           •

QDs are excellent fluorescents and they absorb incident photons at a wavelength and emit lower energy or longer wavelength photon;


                           •

Tunable wavelength range, 400–4000nm: QDs absorb over a broad spectrum of light and fluoresce over a narrow range of wavelengths. This is possible by varying the particle sizes;


                           •

A single excitation wave length can trigger QDs of different size to emit different colors making them ideal for simultaneous imaging of multiple targets (multiplexing);


                           •

QDs can be made to fluoresce in near-infrared (NIR) region of the spectrum. For reduced autofluorescence of the samples (nonspecific background signals due to fluorescence of endogenous cell substances such as nicotinamide coenzymes).

The chemical modification of hydrophobic QDs into water-soluble forms are time-consuming and also result in decreased PL yield. To overcome these problems, the hydrophilic QDs can be directly synthesized by various approaches that include direct synthesis in aqueous media; ligand exchange method, where hydrophobic ligand are exchanged with hydrophilic ligands; or addition of hydrophilic shells around the hydrophobic QDs.

                           •

Ligand exchange/cap exchange: bifunctional amphiphilic molecules are used here in place of the hydrophobic layer of organic solvent. The molecules contain soft acidic groups (mono/poly thiols like sodium thiolycolate) and hydrophilic groups (carboxylic or amino groups) that are projected outward from the QD surfaces toward water molecules (Fig. 12.6
                              );


                           •

Silica shelling: During polycondensation reaction, a silica shell can be covered onto the nanoparticles with a silica precursor of alkoxysilanes (tetraethylorthosilicate).

A glucose sensor is designed for the clinical diagnosis of diabetes using CdTe/CdS QDs that are sensitive to glucose concentration. Glucose oxidase (GO
                        x
                     ) catalyzes conversion of glucose into gluconic acid with the production of hydrogen peroxide that subsequently quenches the QDs PL (Fig. 12.10
                     ). The reduction in QDs PL was proportional to the concentration of glucose from 1.8μM to 1mM with the detection limit of 1.8μM
